AGI -&nbsp;&nbsp; The result of the administrative elections in Turkey fell as a hurricane on the Akp party of President Recep Tayyip Erdogan. The latter not only failed the mission of reconquering the fundamental metropolis of Istanbul, but had to take on a hard defeat in large part of the country, a hemorrhage of votes costed to Akp> the first party of Turkey after 22 years. In addition to losing, with considerable detachment, in the five largest cities in the country, the President's Akp gave strongholds such as Adiyaman, Afyon, Sivas, three of the 11 lost cities where the power of the Erdogan party had been solid in recent years. A defeat that corresponds to the triumph of the Republican party Chp, which for the first time since 1977 exceeded the threshold of 27%, becoming first party with 37.7% of the preferences obtained. To make these results even more surprising the fact that just 10 months ago the Turkish president won the presidential elections at the expense of the then secretary of the Chp, Kemal Kilicdaroglu. What caused such a serious collapse in such a short time? Ten months ago, Erdogan appeared as the most credible alternative to a country in an economic crisis and was reduced by the devastating earthquake of 6 February 2023. >Voting for the president's confirmation seemed a way much more secure than a secluded and fragmented opposition.
&nbsp;
On the contrary, Chp and the other parties have proven to be able to compact at local level and propose alternative governance models to Akp, now in slow decline. The Erdogan party has tried, without success, to propose candidates on a local basis, trying to move attention from the problems of the country and the difficulties of the government. Erdogan has made comity in all the cities, but has avoided harsh tones and frontal confrontation. The election campaign took place very quietly when compared to what happened in the past. People expected a faster turn in economy. On the contrary, inflation has only slowed down, but it keeps on levels that have direct effects on the cost of living for citizens. He has certainly not strengthened the confidence of the voters the recent, yet, change of the director of the Central Bank. The fact that the turnout, although high, was 78.5%, the lowest since 2004, indicates the fact that to stay at home they were disappointed voters of Erdogan.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
Based on studies published by statistical institutes, a large part of the abstained corresponds to about 16 million pensioners in the country. The minimum pension is 41% below the minimum wage > An important part of the voter, who had given confidence to Erdogan in the past, but for months he has been asking for adjustments in line with the cost of life, that the government has not had enough budget to guarantee. A situation that has created anger and detachment in large part of the country, which has seen its purchasing power crushed before the increase in real estate costs and rents. At the defeat of Erdogan the growth of the extreme right and conservative parties is also paid. The Conservative Islamic Party New Refah, alongside Erdogan 10 months ago, captured the votes of disappointed religious and accused the Turkish government of "having sold Gaza to Israel", having given the free way to Lgbtq movements and of course the economic situation. They were also disappointed by the change in monetary policy, convinced that the road to follow was that of the continuous cut of interests and not of the increases made after the 2023 elections. Results: New Refah doubles preferences and passes to 2.8 million votes conquering two provinces where Akp had dominated over the last two decades, Akp has passed from 20.5 million votes of the 2019 administrative to 16.3 two days ago. The hemorrhage of votes of the Erdogan party is explained with the success of New Refah and abstentionism, but in the large cities in many have turned their backs to Erdogan to vote Chp, whose growth remains a central figure. The question is whether the Turkish President will have the energies and the desire to get back to work to recover the lost ground.
&nbsp;
By now seventy-year-old, an Erdogan appeared tired has let it be understood that it will not run for the next elections and the last election campaign showed the minority of the Akp party beyond its leader.&nbsp;

